---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Signs of AuDHD: Symptoms of Autism + ADHD"
  description="Recognize the signs of AuDHD (autism + ADHD). Learn about contradictory traits, social struggles, sensory issues, and the push-pull experience."
  type="article"
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text">Signs of AuDHD</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-text-light leading-relaxed">
        AuDHD symptoms don't look like a simple checklist of "autism traits + ADHD traits." The two conditions interact, mask each other, and create patterns that neither diagnosis fully explains on its own. Here's what to actually look for.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">The Push-Pull Experience</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          The single most defining feature of AuDHD is internal contradiction. Your autism and ADHD want opposite things, and you're caught in the middle. This isn't occasional ambivalence. It's a daily, sometimes hourly, tug-of-war.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          You desperately want a morning routine but can't make yourself do the same thing twice in a row. You need quiet to function but get restless in silence. You plan your week in meticulous detail, then impulsively throw the whole plan out the window on Tuesday because something shiny appeared. Sound familiar?
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Social Signs</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Social situations hit AuDHD people from two angles at once. The autism side makes social rules feel like a foreign language you're constantly translating in real-time. The ADHD side makes you interrupt people, blurt things out, or zone out mid-conversation even when you genuinely care.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Common patterns include:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-text-light leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
          <li>Craving deep, meaningful friendships but struggling to maintain them because you forget to reply to messages for weeks</li>
          <li>Talking at length about your interests, then suddenly realizing you've dominated the entire conversation</li>
          <li>Feeling exhausted after socializing (autism) while also feeling restless and lonely when alone too long (ADHD)</li>
          <li>Reading social cues inconsistently. Sometimes you're incredibly perceptive; other times you miss obvious signals</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Sensory Patterns</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Sensory processing in AuDHD is complicated. You might be hypersensitive to certain inputs (fluorescent lighting, food textures, clothing tags) while actively seeking intense stimulation elsewhere. Blasting music through headphones while being unable to tolerate the sound of someone chewing? Classic AuDHD.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Stimming often combines traits from both conditions. Autistic stimming tends toward repetitive, rhythmic movements (rocking, hand flapping). ADHD stimming leans toward fidgeting, tapping, and movement. AuDHD stimming can look like both, sometimes switching depending on whether you're overstimulated or understimulated. You might rock when anxious and fidget when bored, all within the same hour.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Executive Function Chaos</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Both autism and ADHD affect executive function, but in different ways. ADHD makes it hard to start tasks, especially boring ones. Autism makes it hard to switch between tasks or handle unexpected changes. Put them together and you get someone who can't start the thing, can't switch to a different thing, and melts down when the plan changes.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Specific signs to watch for:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-text-light leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
          <li><strong class="text-text">Task paralysis with a side of guilt:</strong> knowing exactly what you need to do, having a detailed plan, and physically not being able to begin</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Hyperfocus traps:</strong> sinking 8 hours into organizing your bookshelf by color while the deadline looms</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Time blindness meets rigid time awareness:</strong> being obsessively early to appointments you're anxious about, catastrophically late to everything else</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">All-or-nothing productivity:</strong> either producing nothing for weeks or working at an unsustainable pace for days</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Emotional Signs</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Emotional dysregulation shows up in both autism and ADHD. In AuDHD, it can be intense. Rejection sensitivity (common in ADHD) combines with difficulty identifying your own emotions (alexithymia, common in autism) to create situations where you're having a massive emotional reaction and <em>you don't even know what you're feeling.</em>
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Meltdowns and shutdowns can also look different from autism alone. An autistic meltdown typically comes from sensory or emotional overload. An AuDHD meltdown might start from ADHD frustration (lost keys, can't focus, running late again) that snowballs into full autistic shutdown. The triggers are mixed. The experience is overwhelming either way.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Daily Life and Masking</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          AuDHD masking is a double layer. You're masking autistic traits (scripting conversations, forcing eye contact, suppressing stims) while <em>also</em> masking ADHD traits (pretending to pay attention, hiding your disorganization, compensating for forgetfulness with excessive lists and alarms). The energy cost is enormous.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Many AuDHD people describe hitting a wall in their late 20s or 30s when the masking becomes unsustainable. Burnout is almost universal. And because neither condition is visible to others (especially when masked), the exhaustion gets dismissed as laziness, anxiety, or "just being dramatic."
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          If this list reads like a personal biography, that's worth paying attention to.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 bg-accent/10 rounded-[--radius-xl] p-6 sm:p-8">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-text mb-3">Explore More</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2">
        <li><a href="/quiz/is-it-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Take the AuDHD Quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/learn/audhd-in-women/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">How AuDHD presents in women &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/learn/what-is-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">What is AuDHD? &rarr;</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
